[src:fsharp/common-language-runtime] The **Common Language Runtime** (**CLR**), the virtual machine component of Microsoft .NET Framework, manages the execution of .NET programs.
[src:fsharp/common-language-runtime] Just-in-time compilation converts the managed code (compiled intermediate language code) into machine instructions which are then executed on the CPU of the computer.
[src:fsharp/common-language-runtime] The CLR provides additional services including memory management, type safety, exception handling, garbage collection, security and thread management.
[src:fsharp/common-language-runtime] All programs written for the .NET Framework, regardless of programming language, are executed in the CLR.
[src:fsharp/common-language-runtime] All versions of the .NET Framework include CLR.
[src:fsharp/common-language-runtime] CLR implements the Virtual Execution System (VES) as defined in the Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) standard, initially developed by Microsoft itself.
[src:fsharp/common-language-runtime] A public standard defines the Common Language Infrastructure specification.
[src:fsharp/common-language-runtime] During the transition from legacy .NET technologies like the .NET Framework and its proprietary runtime to the community-developed .NET Core, the CLR was dubbed **CoreCLR**.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# is developed by the F# Software Foundation, Microsoft and open contributors.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] An open source, cross-platform compiler for F# is available from the F# Software Foundation.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# is a fully supported language in Visual Studio and JetBrains Rider.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] Plug-ins supporting F# exist for many widely used editors including Visual Studio Code, Vim, and Emacs.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# is a member of the ML language family and originated as a .NET Framework implementation of a core of the programming language OCaml.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] It has also been influenced by C#, Python, Haskell, Scala and Erlang.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# uses an open development and engineering process.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] The language evolution process is managed by Don Syme from Microsoft Research as the benevolent dictator for life (BDFL) for the language design, together with the F# Software Foundation.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] Earlier versions of the F# language were designed by Microsoft and Microsoft Research using a closed development process.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# was first included in Visual Studio in the 2010 edition, at the same level as Visual Basic (.NET) and C# (albeit as an option), and remains in all later editions, thus making the language widely available and well-supported.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# originates from Microsoft Research, Cambridge, UK.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] The language was originally designed and implemented by Don Syme, according to whom in the fsharp team, they say the F is for "Fun".
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] Andrew Kennedy contributed to the design of units of measure.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] The Visual F# Tools for Visual Studio are developed by Microsoft.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] The F# Software Foundation developed the F# open-source compiler and tools, incorporating the open-source compiler implementation provided by the Microsoft Visual F# Tools team.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# is a strongly typed functional-first language with a large number of capabilities that are normally found only in functional programming languages, while supporting object-oriented features available in C#.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] Together, these features allow F# programs to be written in a completely functional style and also allow functional and object-oriented styles to be mixed.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# is an expression-based language using eager evaluation and also in some instances lazy evaluation.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] Every statement in F#, including `if` expressions, `try` expressions and loops, is a composable expression with a static type.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] Functions and expressions that do not return any value have a return type of `unit`.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# uses the `let` keyword for binding values to a name.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] New types are defined using the `type` keyword.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] For functional programming, F# provides *tuple*, *record*, *discriminated union*, *list*, *option*, and *result* types.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] A *tuple* represents a set of *n* values, where *n* ≥ 0.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] The value *n* is called the arity of the tuple.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] A 3-tuple would be represented as `(A, B, C)`, where A, B, and C are values of possibly different types.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] A tuple can be used to store values only when the number of values is known at design-time and stays constant during execution.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] A *record* is a type where the data members are named.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] Records can be created as `let r = { Name="AB"; Age=42 }`.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] The `with` keyword is used to create a copy of a record, as in `{ r with Name="CD" }`, which creates a new record by copying `r` and changing the value of the `Name` field (assuming the record created in the last example was named `r`).
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] A discriminated union type is a type-safe version of C unions.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] Values of the union type can correspond to either union case.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] The types of the values carried by each union case is included in the definition of each case.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] The *list* type is an immutable linked list represented either using a `head::tail` notation (`::` is the cons operator) or a shorthand as `[item1; item2; item3]`.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] The *option* type is a discriminated union type with choices `Some(x)` or `None`.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# types may be generic, implemented as generic .NET types.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# supports lambda functions and closures.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] All functions in F# are first class values and are immutable.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] Being first-class values, functions can be passed as arguments to other functions.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] Like other functional programming languages, F# allows function composition using the `>>` and `<<` operators.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# provides *sequence expressions* that define a sequence `seq { ... }`, list `[ ... ]` or array `[| ... |]` through code that generates values.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] forms a sequence of squares of numbers from 0 to 14 by filtering out numbers from the range of numbers from 0 to 25.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] Sequences are generators – values are generated on-demand (i.e., are lazily evaluated) – while lists and arrays are evaluated eagerly.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# uses pattern matching to bind values to names.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] Pattern matching is also used when accessing discriminated unions – the union is value matched against pattern rules and a rule is selected when a match succeeds.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# also supports *active patterns* as a form of extensible pattern matching.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] It is used, for example, when multiple ways of matching on a type exist.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# supports a general syntax for defining compositional computations called *computation expressions*.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] Sequence expressions, asynchronous computations and queries are particular kinds of computation expressions.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] Computation expressions are an implementation of the monad pattern.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] Values and record fields can also be labelled as `mutable`.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] Also, F# supports access to all CLI types and objects such as those defined in the `System.Collections.Generic` namespace defining imperative data structures.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] Like other Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) languages, F# can use CLI types through object-oriented programming.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# object type definitions can be class, struct, interface, enum, or delegate type definitions, corresponding to the definition forms found in C#.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] For example, here is a class with a constructor taking a name and age, and declaring two properties.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# supports asynchronous programming through *asynchronous workflows*.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] The `let!` indicates that the expression on the right (getting the response) should be done asynchronously but the flow should only continue when the result is available.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] In other words, from the point of view of the code block, it is as if getting the response is a blocking call, whereas from the point of view of the system, the thread will not be blocked and may be used to process other flows until the result needed for this one becomes available.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] The async block may be invoked using the `Async.RunSynchronously` function.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] Multiple async blocks can be executed in parallel using the `Async.Parallel` function that takes a list of `async` objects (in the example, `asynctask` is an async object) and creates another async object to run the tasks in the lists in parallel.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] The resultant object is invoked using `Async.RunSynchronously`.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] Inversion of control in F# follows this pattern.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] Since version 6.0, F# supports creating, consuming and returning .NET tasks directly.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] Parallel programming is supported partly through the `Async.Parallel`, `Async.Start` and other operations that run asynchronous blocks in parallel.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] The F# type system supports units of measure checking for numbers: units of measure, such as meters or kilograms, can be assigned to floating point, unsigned integer and signed integer values.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] This allows the compiler to check that arithmetic involving these values is dimensionally consistent, helping to prevent common programming mistakes by ensuring that, for instance, lengths are not mistakenly added to times.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] The units of measure feature integrates with F# type inference to require minimal type annotations in user code.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] The F# static type checker provides this functionality at compile time, but units are erased from the compiled code.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] Consequently, it is not possible to determine a value's unit at runtime.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# allows some forms of syntax customizing via metaprogramming to support embedding custom domain-specific languages within the F# language, particularly through computation expressions.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# includes a feature for run-time meta-programming called quotations.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] A quotation expression evaluates to an abstract syntax tree representation of the F# expressions.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] Similarly, definitions labelled with the `[<ReflectedDefinition>]` attribute can also be accessed in their quotation form.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# quotations are used for various purposes including to compile F# code into JavaScript and GPU code.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] Quotations represent their F# code expressions as data for use by other parts of the program while requiring it to be syntactically correct F# code.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# 3.0 introduced a form of compile-time meta-programming through statically extensible type generation called F# type providers.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# type providers allow the F# compiler and tools to be extended with components that provide type information to the compiler on-demand at compile time.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# type providers have been used to give strongly typed access to connected information sources in a scalable way, including to the Freebase knowledge graph.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] In F# 3.0 the F# quotation and computation expression features are combined to implement LINQ queries.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] The combination of type providers, queries and strongly typed functional programming is known as *information rich programming*.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# supports a variation of the actor programming model through the in-memory implementation of lightweight asynchronous agents.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# is a general-purpose programming language.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] The SAFE Stack is an end-to-end F# stack to develop web applications.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] It uses ASP.NET Core on the server side and Fable on the client side.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] Alternative end-to-end F# options include the WebSharper framework and the Oxpecker framework.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# can be used together with the Visual Studio Tools for Xamarin to develop apps for iOS and Android.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] The Fabulous library provides a more comfortable functional interface.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] Among others, F# is used for quantitative finance programming, energy trading and portfolio optimization, machine learning, business intelligence and social gaming on Facebook.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] In the 2010s, F# has been positioned as an optimized alternative to C#.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F#'s scripting ability and inter-language compatibility with all Microsoft products have made it popular among developers.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# can be used as a scripting language, mainly for desktop read–eval–print loop (REPL) scripting.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] The F# open-source community includes the F# Software Foundation and the F# Open Source Group at GitHub.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] F# features a legacy "ML compatibility mode" that can directly compile programs written in a large subset of OCaml roughly, with no functors, objects, polymorphic variants, or other additions.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] Records are immutable by default and are compared by structural equality.
[src:fsharp/f-sharp-programming-language] A Person class with a constructor taking a name and age and two immutable properties.
